# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boyer-moore-string
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] In computer science, the **Aho–Corasick algorithm** is a string-searching algorithm invented by Alfred V.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] It is a kind of dictionary-matching algorithm that locates elements of a finite set of strings (the "dictionary") within an input text.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] The complexity of the algorithm is linear in the length of the strings plus the length of the searched text plus the number of output matches.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] Because all matches are found, multiple matches will be returned for one string location if multiple strings from the dictionary match at that location (e.g. dictionary = a, aa, aaa, aaaa and input string is aaaa).
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] Informally, the algorithm creates a trie using the strings in the dictionary and then constructs a finite-state machine from the trie by adding additional links between the nodes.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] This allows the automaton to transition between string matches without the need for backtracking.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] When the string dictionary is known in advance (e.g. a computer virus database), the construction of the automaton can be performed once off-line and the compiled automaton stored for later use.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] In this case, its run time is linear in the length of the input plus the number of matched entries.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] The Aho—Corasick string-matching algorithm formed the basis of the original Unix command fgrep.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] Like many inventions at Bell Labs at the time, the Aho–Corasick algorithm was created serendipitously with a conversation between the two after a seminar by Aho.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] Corasick was an information scientist who got her PhD a year earlier at Lehigh University.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] There, she did her dissertation on securing proprietary data within open systems, through the lens of both the commercial, legal, and government structures and the technical tools that were emerging at the time.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] In a similar realm, at Bell Labs, she was building a tool for researchers to learn about current work being done by government contractors by searching government-provided tapes of publications.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] She had written a primitive keyword-by-keyword search program to find chosen keywords within the tapes, but it scaled poorly with many keywords; One of the bibliographers using her algorithm hit the $600 usage limit on the Bell Labs machines before their search finished.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] She ended up attending a seminar on algorithm design by Aho, and afterwards they got to speaking about her work and this problem.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] Aho suggested improving the efficiency of the program using the approach of the now Aho–Corasick algorithm, and Corasick designed a program based on those insights.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] This lowered the running cost of that bibliographer's search from over $600 to just $25.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] In this example, we will consider a dictionary consisting of the following words: {a, ab, bab, bc, bca, c, caa}.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] The graph below is the Aho–Corasick data structure constructed from the specified dictionary, with each row in the table representing a node in the trie, with the column path indicating the (unique) sequence of characters from the root to the node.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] The data structure has one node for every prefix of every string in the dictionary.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] So if (bca) is in the dictionary, then there will be nodes for (bca), (bc), (b), and ().
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] If a node is in the dictionary then it is a blue node.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] There is a black directed "child" arc from each node to a node whose name is found by appending one character.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] So there is a black arc from (bc) to (bca).
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] There is a blue directed "suffix" arc from each node to the node that is the longest possible strict suffix of it in the graph.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] For example, for node (caa), its strict suffixes are (aa) and (a) and ().
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] The longest of these that exists in the graph is (a).
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] So there is a blue arc from (caa) to (a).
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] The blue arcs can be computed in linear time by performing a breadth-first search [potential suffix node will always be at lower level] starting from the root.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] The target for the blue arc of a visited node can be found by following its parent's blue arc to its longest suffix node and searching for a child of the suffix node whose character matches that of the visited node.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] If the character does not exist as a child, we can find the next longest suffix (following the blue arc again) and then search for the character.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] We can do this until we either find the character (as child of a node) or we reach the root (which will always be a suffix of every string).
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] There is a green "dictionary suffix" arc from each node to the next node in the dictionary that can be reached by following blue arcs.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] For example, there is a green arc from (bca) to (a) because (a) is the first node in the dictionary (i.e. a blue node) that is reached when following the blue arcs to (ca) and then on to (a).
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] The green arcs can be computed in linear time by repeatedly traversing blue arcs until a blue node is found, and memoizing this information.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] At each step, the current node is extended by finding its child, and if that doesn't exist, finding its suffix's child, and if that doesn't work, finding its suffix's suffix's child, and so on, finally ending in the root node if nothing's seen before.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] When the algorithm reaches a node, it outputs all the dictionary entries that end at the current character position in the input text.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] This is done by printing every node reached by following the dictionary suffix links, starting from that node, and continuing until it reaches a node with no dictionary suffix link.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] In addition, the node itself is printed, if it is a dictionary entry.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] The original Aho–Corasick algorithm assumes that the set of search strings is fixed.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] It does not directly apply to applications in which new search strings are added during application of the algorithm.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] An example is an interactive indexing program, in which the user goes through the text and highlights new words or phrases to index as they see them.
[src:boyer-moore-string/aho-corasick-algorithm] Bertrand Meyer introduced an incremental version of the algorithm in which the search string set can be incrementally extended during the search, retaining the algorithmic complexity of the original.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In computer science, the **Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm** is an efficient string-searching algorithm that is the standard benchmark for practical string-search literature.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The original paper contained static tables for computing the pattern shifts without an explanation of how to produce them.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The algorithm for producing the tables was published in a follow-on paper; this paper contained errors which were later corrected by Wojciech Rytter in 1980.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The algorithm preprocesses the string being searched for (the pattern), but not the string being searched in (the text).
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] It is thus well-suited for applications in which the pattern is much shorter than the text or where it persists across multiple searches.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm uses information gathered during the preprocess step to skip sections of the text, resulting in a lower constant factor than many other string search algorithms.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In general, the algorithm runs faster as the pattern length increases.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The key features of the algorithm are to match on the tail of the pattern rather than the head, and to skip along the text in jumps of multiple characters rather than searching every single character in the text.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm searches for occurrences of P in T by performing explicit character comparisons at different alignments.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Instead of a brute-force search of all alignments (of which there are ⁠ $n-m+1$ ⁠), Boyer–Moore uses information gained by preprocessing P to skip as many alignments as possible.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Previous to the introduction of this algorithm, the usual way to search within text was to examine each character of the text for the first character of the pattern.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Once that was found the subsequent characters of the text would be compared to the characters of the pattern.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If no match occurred then the text would again be checked character by character in an effort to find a match.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Thus almost every character in the text needs to be examined.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The key insight in this algorithm is that if the end of the pattern is compared to the text, then jumps along the text can be made rather than checking every character of the text.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The reason that this works is that in lining up the pattern against the text, the last character of the pattern is compared to the character in the text.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the characters do not match, there is no need to continue searching backwards along the text.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the character in the text does not match any of the characters in the pattern, then the next character in the text to check is located m characters farther along the text, where m is the length of the pattern.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the character in the text *is* in the pattern, then a partial shift of the pattern along the text is done to line up along the matching character and the process is repeated.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Jumping along the text to make comparisons rather than checking every character in the text decreases the number of comparisons that have to be made, which is the key to the efficiency of the algorithm.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] More formally, the algorithm begins at alignment ⁠ $k=m$ ⁠, so the start of P is aligned with the start of T.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Characters in P and T are then compared starting at index m in P and k in T, moving backward.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The strings are matched from the end of P to the start of P.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The comparisons continue until either the beginning of P is reached (which means there is a match) or a mismatch occurs upon which the alignment is shifted forward (to the right) according to the maximum value permitted by a number of rules.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The comparisons are performed again at the new alignment, and the process repeats until the alignment is shifted past the end of T, which means no further matches will be found.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The shift rules are implemented as constant-time table lookups, using tables generated during the preprocessing of P.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] A shift is calculated by applying two rules: the bad-character rule and the good-suffix rule.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The actual shifting offset is the maximum of the shifts calculated by these rules.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The bad-character rule considers the character in T at which the comparison process failed (assuming such a failure occurred).
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The next occurrence of that character to the left in P is found, and a shift which brings that occurrence in line with the mismatched occurrence in T is proposed.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the mismatched character does not occur to the left in P, a shift is proposed that moves the entirety of P past the point of mismatch.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Methods vary on the exact form the table for the bad-character rule should take, but a simple constant-time lookup solution is as follows: create a 2D table which is indexed first by the index of the character c in the alphabet and second by the index i in the pattern.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This lookup will return the occurrence of c in P with the next-highest index ⁠ $j<i$ ⁠ or -1 if there is no such occurrence.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The proposed shift will then be ⁠ $i-j$ ⁠, with ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠ lookup time and ⁠ $O(km)$ ⁠ space, assuming a finite alphabet of length k.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The C and Java implementations below have a ⁠ $O(k)$ ⁠ space complexity (make_delta1, makeCharTable).
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This is the same as the original delta1 and the BMH bad-character table.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This table maps a character at position ⁠ i ⁠ to shift by ⁠ $\operatorname {len} (p)-1-i$ ⁠, with the last instance—the least shift amount—taking precedence.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] All unused characters are set as ⁠ $\operatorname {len} (p)$ ⁠ as a sentinel value.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The good-suffix rule is markedly more complex in both concept and implementation than the bad-character rule.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Like the bad-character rule, it also exploits the algorithm's feature of comparisons beginning at the end of the pattern and proceeding towards the pattern's start.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The good-suffix rule requires two tables: one for use in the general case (where a copy ***t′*** is found), and another for use when the general case returns no meaningful result.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] These tables will be designated L and H respectively.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Both of these tables are constructible in ⁠ $O(m)$ ⁠ time and use ⁠ $O(m)$ ⁠ space.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The alignment shift for index i in P is given by ⁠ $m-L[i]$ ⁠ or ⁠ $m-H[i]$ ⁠.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] H should only be used if ⁠ $L[i]$ ⁠ is zero or a match has been found.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 0, no characters matched, the character read was not an N.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Since there are plenty of letters in the pattern that are also not N, we have minimal information here - shifting by 1 is the least interesting result.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 1, we matched the N, and it was preceded by something other than A.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Now look at the pattern starting from the end, where do we have N preceded by something other than A?
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] There are two other N's, but both are preceded by A.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] That means no part of the good suffix can be useful to us—shift by the full pattern length 8.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 2: We matched the AN, and it was preceded by not M.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In the middle of the pattern there is a AN preceded by P, so it becomes the shift candidate.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Shifting that AN to the right to line up with our match is a shift of 3.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 3 & up: the matched suffixes do not match anything else in the pattern, but the trailing suffix AN matches the start of the pattern, so the shifts here are all 6.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] A simple but important optimization of Boyer–Moore was put forth by Zvi Galil in 1979.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] As opposed to shifting, the Galil rule deals with speeding up the actual comparisons done at each alignment by skipping sections that are known to match.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Suppose that at an alignment *k*1, ***P*** is compared with ***T*** down to character ***c*** of ***T***.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Then if ***P*** is shifted to *k*2 such that its left end is between ***c*** and *k*1, in the next comparison phase a prefix of ***P*** must match the substring ***T***[(*k*2 - *n*)..*k*1].
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Thus if the comparisons get down to position *k*1 of ***T***, an occurrence of ***P*** can be recorded without explicitly comparing past *k*1.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In addition to increasing the efficiency of Boyer–Moore, the Galil rule is required for proving linear-time execution in the worst case.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Galil rule, in its original version, is only effective for versions that output multiple matches.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] It updates the substring range only on ***c*** = 0, i.e. a full match.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] A generalized version for dealing with submatches was reported in 1985 as the Apostolico–Giancarlo algorithm.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm as presented in the original paper has worst-case running time of ⁠ $O(n+m)$ ⁠ only if the pattern does *not* appear in the text.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This was first proved by Knuth, Morris, and Pratt in 1977, followed by Guibas and Odlyzko in 1980 with an upper bound of 5*n* comparisons in the worst case.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Richard Cole gave a proof with an upper bound of 3*n* comparisons in the worst case in 1991.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] There is a simple modification of the BM algorithm which improves the bound to 2*n*.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] When the pattern *does* occur in the text, running time of the original algorithm is ⁠ $O(nm)$ ⁠ in the worst case.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This is easy to see when both pattern and text consist solely of the same repeated character.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] However, inclusion of the Galil rule results in linear runtime across all cases.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Knuth, Morris and Pratt also showed that for a *random* text, the average number of character comparisons is bounded by $O\left({\frac {n\log _{k}m}{m}}\right)$ , where k is the alphabet size.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Various implementations exist in different programming languages.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In C++ it is part of the Standard Library since C++17 and Boost provides the generic Boyer–Moore search implementation under the *Algorithm* library.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In Go (programming language) there is an implementation in search.go.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] D (programming language) uses a BoyerMooreFinder for predicate based matching within ranges as a part of the Phobos Runtime Library.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm is also used in GNU's grep.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore–Horspool algorithm is a simplification of the Boyer–Moore algorithm using only the bad-character rule.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Apostolico–Giancarlo algorithm speeds up the process of checking whether a match has occurred at the given alignment by skipping explicit character comparisons.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This uses information gleaned during the pre-processing of the pattern in conjunction with suffix match lengths recorded at each match attempt.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Storing suffix match lengths requires an additional table equal in size to the text being searched.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Raita algorithm improves the performance of Boyer–Moore–Horspool algorithm.
[src:boyer-moore-string/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The searching pattern of particular sub-string in a given string is different from Boyer–Moore–Horspool algorithm.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Morris and independently discovered by Donald Knuth "a few weeks later" from automata theory.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Morris and Vaughan Pratt published a technical report in 1970.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The three also published the algorithm jointly in 1977.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Independently, in 1969, Matiyasevich discovered a similar algorithm, coded by a two-dimensional Turing machine, while studying a string-pattern-matching recognition problem over a binary alphabet.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This was the first linear-time algorithm for string matching.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] A string-matching algorithm wants to find the starting index `m` in string `s` that matches the search word `w`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The most straightforward algorithm, known as the "brute-force" or "naive" algorithm, is to look for a word match at each index `m`, i.e. the position in the string being searched that corresponds to the character `s[m]`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] At each position `m` the algorithm first checks for equality of the first character in the word being searched, i.e.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If a match is found, the algorithm tests the other characters in the word being searched by checking successive values of the word position index, `i`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The algorithm retrieves the character `w[i]` in the word being searched and checks for equality of the expression `S[m+i] =?
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If all successive characters match in `W` at position `m`, then a match is found at that position in the search string.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the index `m` reaches the end of the string then there is no match, in which case the search is said to "fail".
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Usually, the trial check will quickly reject the trial match.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the strings are uniformly distributed random letters, then the chance that characters match is 1 in 26.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In most cases, the trial check will reject the match at the initial letter.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The chance that the first two letters will match is 1 in 676 (1 in 26^2 chances of a match over 26 possible letters).
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] So if the characters are random, then the expected complexity of searching string `s` of length *n* is on the order of *n* comparisons or *Θ*(*n*).
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If `s` is 1 million characters and `w` is 1000 characters, then the string search should complete after about 1.04 million character comparisons.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] That expected performance is not guaranteed.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the strings are not random, then checking a trial `m` may take many character comparisons.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The worst case is if the two strings match in all but the last letter.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Imagine that the string `s` consists of 1 million characters that are all *A*, and that the word `w` is 999 *A* characters terminating in a final *B* character.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The simple string-matching algorithm will now examine 1000 characters at each trial position before rejecting the match and advancing the trial position.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The simple string search example would now take about 1000 character comparisons times 1 million positions for 1 billion character comparisons.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the length of `w` is *k*, then the worst-case performance is *O*(*k*⋅*n*).
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The KMP algorithm has a better worst-case performance than the straightforward algorithm.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] KMP spends a little time precomputing a table (on the order of the size of `w`, *O*(*k*)), and then it uses that table to do an efficient search of the string in *O*(*n*).
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The difference is that KMP makes use of previous match information that the straightforward algorithm does not.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In the example above, when KMP sees a trial match fail on the 1000th character (`i` = 999) because `s[m + 999] ≠ w[999]`, it will increment `m` by 1, but it will know that the first 998 characters at the new position already match.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] KMP matched 999 *A* characters before discovering a mismatch at the 1000th character (position 999).
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Advancing the trial match position `m` by one throws away the first *A*, so KMP knows there are 998 *A* characters that match `w` and does not retest them; that is, KMP sets `i` to 998.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] KMP maintains its knowledge in the precomputed table and two state variables.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] When KMP discovers a mismatch, the table determines how much KMP will increase (variable `m`) and where it will resume testing (variable `i`).
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] To illustrate the algorithm's details, consider a (relatively artificial) run of the algorithm, where `W` = "ABCDABD" and `S` = "ABC ABCDAB ABCDABCDABDE".
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In each step the algorithm compares `S[m+i]` with `W[i]` and increments `i` if they are equal.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The algorithm compares successive characters of `W` to "parallel" characters of `S`, moving from one to the next by incrementing `i` if they match.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] However, in the fourth step `S[3] = ' '` does not match `W[3] = 'D'`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Rather than beginning to search again at `S[1]`, we note that no `'A'` occurs between positions 1 and 2 in `S`; hence, having checked all those characters previously (and knowing they matched the corresponding characters in `W`), there is no chance of finding the beginning of a match.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Therefore, the algorithm sets `m = 3` and `i = 0`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Here, `i` increments through a nearly complete match `"ABCDAB"` until `i = 6` giving a mismatch at `W[6]` and `S[10]`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] However, just prior to the end of the current partial match, there was that substring `"AB"` that could be the beginning of a new match, so the algorithm must take this into consideration.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] As these characters match the two characters prior to the current position, those characters need not be checked again; the algorithm sets `m = 8` (the start of the initial prefix) and `i = 2` (signaling the first two characters match) and continues matching.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus the algorithm not only omits previously matched characters of `S` (the `"AB"`), but also previously matched characters of `W` (the prefix `"AB"`).
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This search at the new position fails immediately because `W[2]` (a `'C'`) does not match `S[10]` (a `' '`).
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] As in the first trial, the mismatch causes the algorithm to return to the beginning of `W` and begins searching at the mismatched character position of `S`: `m = 10`, reset `i = 0`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The match at `m=10` fails immediately, so the algorithm next tries `m = 11` and `i = 0`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Once again, the algorithm matches `"ABCDAB"`, but the next character, `'C'`, does not match the final character `'D'` of the word `W`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Reasoning as before, the algorithm sets `m = 15`, to start at the two-character string `"AB"` leading up to the current position, set `i = 2`, and continue matching from the current position.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This time the match is complete, and the first character of the match is `S[15]`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The above example contains all the elements of the algorithm.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] For the moment, we assume the existence of a "partial match" table `T`, described below, which indicates where we need to look for the start of a new match when a mismatch is found.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The entries of `T` are constructed so that if we have a match starting at `S[m]` that fails when comparing `S[m + i]` to `W[i]`, then the next possible match will start at index `m + i - T[i]` in `S` (that is, `T[i]` is the amount of "backtracking" we need to do after a mismatch).
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The following is a sample pseudocode implementation of the KMP search algorithm.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Assuming the prior existence of the table `T`, the search portion of the Knuth–Morris–Pratt algorithm has complexity *O*(*n*), where *n* is the length of `S` and the *O* is big-O notation.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Except for the fixed overhead incurred in entering and exiting the function, all the computations are performed in the `**while**` loop.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] To bound the number of iterations of this loop; observe that `T` is constructed so that if a match which had begun at `S[m]` fails while comparing `S[m + i]` to `W[i]`, then the next possible match must begin at `S[m + (i - T[i])]`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In particular, the next possible match must occur at a higher index than `m`, so that `T[i] < i`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This fact implies that the loop can execute at most 2*n* times, since at each iteration it executes one of the two branches in the loop.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The first branch invariably increases `i` and does not change `m`, so that the index `m + i` of the currently scrutinized character of `S` is increased.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The second branch adds `i - T[i]` to `m`, and as we have seen, this is always a positive number.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus the location `m` of the beginning of the current potential match is increased.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] At the same time, the second branch leaves `m + i` unchanged, for `m` gets `i - T[i]` added to it, and immediately after `T[i]` gets assigned as the new value of `i`, hence `new_m + new_i = old_m + old_i - T[old_i] + T[old_i] = old_m + old_i`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus the loop executes at most 2*n* times, showing that the time complexity of the search algorithm is *O*(*n*).
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Here is another way to think about the runtime: Let us say we begin to match `W` and `S` at position `i` and `p`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If `W` exists as a substring of `S` at p, then `W[0..m] = S[p..p+m]`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Upon success, that is, the word and the text matched at the positions (`W[i] = S[p+i]`), we increase `i` by 1.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Upon failure, that is, the word and the text do not match at the positions (`W[i] ≠ S[p+i]`), the text pointer is kept still, while the word pointer is rolled back a certain amount (`i = T[i]`, where `T` is the jump table), and we attempt to match `W[T[i]]` with `S[p+i]`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The maximum number of roll-back of `i` is bounded by `i`, that is to say, for any failure, we can only roll back as much as we have progressed up to the failure.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The goal of the table is to allow the algorithm not to match any character of `S` more than once.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In other words, we "pre-search" the pattern itself and compile a list of all possible fallback positions that bypass a maximum of hopeless characters while not sacrificing any potential matches in doing so.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Hence `T[i]` is exactly the length of the longest possible *proper* initial segment of `W` which is also a segment of the substring ending at `W[i - 1]`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We use the convention that the empty string has length 0.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Since a mismatch at the very start of the pattern is a special case (there is no possibility of backtracking), we set `T[0] = -1`, as discussed below.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We consider the example of `W = "ABCDABD"` first.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We will see that it follows much the same pattern as the main search, and is efficient for similar reasons.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] To find `T[1]`, we must discover a proper suffix of `"A"` which is also a prefix of pattern `W`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] But there are no proper suffixes of `"A"`, so we set `T[1] = 0`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] However "B" is not a prefix of the pattern `W`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Continuing to `T[3]`, we first check the proper suffix of length 1, and as in the previous case it fails.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Hence at each stage, the shortcut rule is that one needs to consider checking suffixes of a given size m+1 only if a valid suffix of size m was found at the previous stage (i.e.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] `T[x] = m`) and should not bother to check m+2, m+3, etc.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Therefore, we need not even concern ourselves with substrings having length 2, and as in the previous case the sole one with length 1 fails, so `T[3] = 0`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We pass to the subsequent `W[4]`, `'A'`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The same logic shows that the longest substring we need to consider has length 1, and as in the previous case it fails since "D" is not a prefix of `W`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] But instead of setting `T[4] = 0`, we can do better by noting that `W[4] = W[0]`, and also that a look-up of `T[4]` implies the corresponding `S` character, `S[m+4]`, was a mismatch and therefore `S[m+4] ≠ 'A'`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus there is no point in restarting the search at `S[m+4]`; we should begin at 1 position ahead.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This means that we may shift pattern `W` by match length plus one character, so `T[4] = -1`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Considering now the next character, `W[5]`, which is `'B'`: though by inspection the longest substring would appear to be `'A'`, we still set `T[5] = 0`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The reasoning is similar to why `T[4] = -1`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] `W[5]` itself extends the prefix match begun with `W[4]`, and we can assume that the corresponding character in `S`, `S[m+5] ≠ 'B'`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Finally, we see that the next character in the ongoing segment starting at `W[4] = 'A'` would be `'B'`, and indeed this is also `W[5]`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Furthermore, the same argument as above shows that we need not look before `W[4]` to find a segment for `W[6]`, so that this is it, and we take `T[6] = 2`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The example above illustrates the general technique for assembling the table with a minimum of fuss.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The principle is that of the overall search: most of the work was already done in getting to the current position, so very little needs to be done in leaving it.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The only minor complication is that the logic which is correct late in the string erroneously gives non-proper substrings at the beginning.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This necessitates some initialization code.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The time (and space) complexity of the table algorithm is $O(k)$ , where k is the length of `W`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Combined, the outer and inner loops take at most $2k-2$ iterations.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This corresponds to $O(k)$ time complexity using the Big O notation.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Since the two portions of the algorithm have, respectively, complexities of `O(k)` and `O(n)`, the complexity of the overall algorithm is `O(n + k)`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] These complexities are independent of how many repetitive patterns are in `W` or `S`.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] It is known that the delay, that is the number of times a symbol of the text is compared to symbols of the pattern, is less than $\lfloor \log _{\Phi }(k+1)\rfloor$ , where Φ is the golden ration $(1+{\sqrt {5}})/2$ .
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In 1993, an algorithm was given that has a delay bounded by $\min(1+\lfloor \log _{2}k\rfloor ,|\Sigma |)$ where Σ is the size of the alphabet (of the pattern).
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] A real-time version of KMP can be implemented using a separate failure function table for each character in the alphabet.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If a mismatch occurs on character x in the text, the failure function table for character x is consulted for the index i in the pattern at which the mismatch took place.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This will return the length of the longest substring ending at i matching a prefix of the pattern, with the added condition that the character after the prefix is x .
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] With this restriction, character x in the text need not be checked again in the next phase, and so only a constant number of operations are executed between the processing of each index of the text.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This satisfies the real-time computing restriction.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Booth's algorithm uses a modified version of the KMP preprocessing function to find the lexicographically minimal string rotation.
[src:boyer-moore-string/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The failure function is progressively calculated as the string is rotated.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] A **string-searching algorithm**, sometimes called **string-matching algorithm**, is an algorithm that searches a body of text for portions that match by pattern.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] In practice, the method of feasible string-search algorithm may be affected by the string encoding.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] In particular, if a variable-width encoding is in use, then it may be slower to find the *N*th character, perhaps requiring time proportional to *N*.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] This may significantly slow some search algorithms.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] One of many possible solutions is to search for the sequence of code units instead, but doing so may produce false matches unless the encoding is specifically designed to avoid it.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] The most basic case of string searching involves one (often very long) string, sometimes called the *haystack*, and one (often very short) string, sometimes called the *needle*.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] The goal is to find one or more occurrences of the needle within the haystack.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] One might request the first occurrence of "to", which is the fourth word; or all occurrences, of which there are 3; or the last, which is the fifth word from the end.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] Very commonly, however, various constraints are added.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] For example, one might want to match the "needle" only where it consists of one (or more) complete words—perhaps defined as *not* having other letters immediately adjacent on either side.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] In that case a search for "hew" or "low" should fail for the example sentence above, even though those literal strings do occur.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] Another common example involves "normalization".
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] Finally, for strings that represent natural language, aspects of the language itself become involved.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] For example, one might wish to find all occurrences of a "word" despite it having alternate spellings, prefixes or suffixes, etc.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] Another more complex type of search is regular expression searching, where the user constructs a pattern of characters or other symbols, and any match to the pattern should fulfill the search.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] where the "?" conventionally makes the preceding character ("u") optional.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] This article mainly discusses algorithms for the simpler kinds of string searching.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] A similar problem introduced in the field of bioinformatics and genomics is the maximal exact matching (MEM).
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] Given two strings, MEMs are common substrings that cannot be extended left or right without causing a mismatch.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] A simple and inefficient way to see where one string occurs inside another is to check at each index, one by one.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] First, we see if there is a copy of the needle starting at the first character of the haystack; if not, we look to see if there's a copy of the needle starting at the second character of the haystack, and so forth.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] In this approach, backtracking is avoided by constructing a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) that recognizes a stored search string.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] These are expensive to construct—they are usually created using the powerset construction—but are very quick to use.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] For example, the DFA shown to the right recognizes the word "MOMMY".
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] This approach is frequently generalized in practice to search for arbitrary regular expressions.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] Knuth–Morris–Pratt computes a DFA that recognizes inputs with the string to search for as a suffix, Boyer–Moore starts searching from the end of the needle, so it can usually jump ahead a whole needle-length at each step.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] Baeza–Yates keeps track of whether the previous *j* characters were a prefix of the search string, and is therefore adaptable to fuzzy string searching.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] The bitap algorithm is an application of Baeza–Yates' approach.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] Faster search algorithms preprocess the text.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] After building a substring index, for example a suffix tree or suffix array, the occurrences of a pattern can be found quickly.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] As an example, a suffix tree can be built in $\Theta (n)$ time, and all z occurrences of a pattern can be found in $O(m)$ time under the assumption that the alphabet has a constant size and all inner nodes in the suffix tree know what leaves are underneath them.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] The latter can be accomplished by running a DFS algorithm from the root of the suffix tree.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] Some search methods, for instance trigram search, are intended to find a "closeness" score between the search string and the text rather than a "match/non-match".
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] These are sometimes called "fuzzy" searches.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] The various algorithms can be classified by the number of patterns each uses.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] In the following compilation, *m* is the length of the pattern, *n* the length of the searchable text, and *k* = |Σ| is the size of the alphabet.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] The **Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm** has been the standard benchmark for the practical string-search literature.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] In the following compilation, *M* is the length of the longest pattern, *m* their total length, *n* the length of the searchable text, *o* the number of occurrences.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] Naturally, the patterns can not be enumerated finitely in this case.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] They are represented usually by a regular grammar or regular expression.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] Other classification approaches are possible.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] One of the most common uses preprocessing as main criteria.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] In real-time string matching, one requires the matcher to output a response after reading each character of the text, that indicates whether this is the last character of a match.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] The response has to be given within constant time.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] For the more lenient version, if one does not mind that the preprocessing time and memory requirement dependend on the size of the alphabet, a real-time solution is provided by automaton matching.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] Zvi Galil developed a method to turn certain algorithms into real-time algorithms, and applied it to produce a variant of the KMP matcher that runs in real time under the strict requirement.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] In this version of the string searching problem, there is a special symbol, ø (read: don't care), which can match any other symbol (including another ø).
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] Don't care symbols can appear either in the pattern or in the text.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] In 2002, an algorithm for this problem that runs in $O(n\log m)$ time has been given by Richard Cole and Ramesh Hariharan, improving on a solution from 1973 by Fischer and Paterson that has complexity $O(n\log m\log k)$ , where *k* is the size of the alphabet.
[src:boyer-moore-string/string-searching-algorithm] Another algorithm, claimed simpler, has been proposed by Clifford and Clifford.
[src:boyer-moore-string/substring-index] In computer science, a **substring index** is a data structure which gives substring search in a text or text collection in sublinear time.
[src:boyer-moore-string/substring-index] Once constructed from a document or set of documents, a substring index can be used to locate all occurrences of a pattern in time linear or near-linear in the pattern size, with no dependence or only logarithmic dependence on the document size.
[src:boyer-moore-string/substring-index] The phrase **full-text index** is often used for substring indexes.
[src:boyer-moore-string/substring-index] But this is ambiguous, as it is also used for regular word indexes such as inverted files and document retrieval.
[src:boyer-moore-string/substring-index] These data structures typically treat their text and pattern as strings over a fixed alphabet, and search for locations where the pattern occurs as a substring of the text.
